The translation of "Die Ukraine auf dem Weg nach Europa" from German to English is:  "Ukraine on the path to Europe"
"East is East and West is West, and never the twain shall meet," Rudyard Kipling once said.
The translation of the given German sentence to English is:  "Although Ukraine undoubtedly lies in the east, it is in Eastern Europe."
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the dominant goal for many of us.
The path there, however, was not always paved with successes if it was paved at all.
But the result of the parliamentary elections on March 31 showed that Ukrainians are still determined to go down this path.
I am a Social Democrat and have never been a member of the communist party, although as a lawyer during the time of the Soviet Union, I was certainly successful.
It is beyond question for me that our "Soviet" legacy is largely responsible for Ukraine's difficulties in joining Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The huge agricultural cultivation areas were practically rendered ineffective by outdated machine parks and the inertia of state-run agriculture, which followed the Soviet model.
The rural population sank deep into dirt and poverty.
Low wages make life here very burdensome, the pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is enormous.
But our Soviet heritage does not justify everything.
We have completely bungled the reform all on our own.
For often we wanted to import proven concepts from the West - private property, free market economy, strict observance of human rights, the creation of civil society, and representative democracy - in a diluted form and believed that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic tendencies in politics, the Supreme Council (the Parliament of Ukraine) has over the years adopted citizens' rights and criminal law, as well as land, family, and economic rights, which is akin to a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that was cut off from European history for centuries was often painful, but it has gained momentum, although we do not necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as open, sentimental, friendly, and family-conscious, but also chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Nevertheless, we are Europeans.
This can be seen on the streets and squares of Kyiv.
Today, drivers let pedestrians cross the street, as in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to take precautions against thoughtless drivers).
In Kiev, there is now a lively café scene and friendly public spaces where people can pause and enjoy life.
The young people learn English, German, and French, they can handle computers and surf the internet at the Internet Cafés.
But these are merely the ramblings of someone who loves Kyiv very much.
The sober gaze of the career politician that I am sees profound changes.
Over the last ten years, a development has taken place from total rejection of reforms to a policy of half-hearted reforms motivated by corruption, and finally to a gradual introduction of Western practices.
The administrative reform reflects this very vividly.
First, the reform of the state stirred up hostile feelings among both bureaucrats and ordinary citizens.
A drastic and unconsidered reduction of public servants began.
It was a reform "in the mold of F": it was assumed that the state had to shrink, and then the government would run smoothly.
No one thought about how countries like France or Switzerland manage to thrive despite having large public administrations.
The problem is not only a matter of size, but also of organization and appropriateness.
The realization that the government does not necessarily become better simply by putting pen to paper led us to the second stage in our reform process.
Slowly, the state was reformed in a more reasonable way.
New departments and positions for ministers with clearly defined areas of responsibility were established.
Thereby, the work of the government ministries was stabilized.
At the beginning, the authority transferred to these new areas was too broad to help them work more effectively.
Now they are functioning more or less normally.
Perhaps Ukrainians sometimes irritate over these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they increasingly accept them as necessary (though reluctantly).
Rational politicians also accept them.
Only radicals and populists - of whom we still have too many - can afford to adopt an indifferent attitude towards a more efficient state.
The taming of our radicals and the radical impulse was not simple.
Why?
The Ukraine was for too long a province of the USSR and the Tsarist Empire, the most important, but still a province.
This has shaped our mentality. For radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming sense of inferiority and our efforts to deny this have led to some of the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial leader can never admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
To the extent that we shed our provincial tendency to feel we must defend ourselves, we open ourselves up to the best that others can offer us.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire wasmocked as "the sick man of Europe."
Since 1991, the Ukrainians have had to acknowledge that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
Over the course of a decade, we may have contributed to becoming even sicker ourselves, but the recent elections that deprived the Communists of their dominant position in the Supreme Council and significantly reduced the power of the "powerful parties" under President Kuchma have pushed our provincial radicals to the political margins.
The reform parties and the European parties have won.
As European outsiders, or rather as a people on the periphery of Europe, we want to build a society in which there are no outsiders or marginal individuals.
As the great and already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Of all achievements of nature, the most astounding probably is the survival of the weakest."
The long, austere journey to Europe has helped a weak new nation become strong and survive.
